[[File:Cartonnage à la Bradel.jpg|thumb]]

{{multiple issues|
{{refimprove|date=August 2011}}
{{notability|Products|date=August 2011}}
}}

A '''Bradel''' binding (also called a bonnet or bristol board binding, a ''German Case'' binding, or in French as ''Cartonnage à la Bradel'' or ''en gist'') is a style of [[book binding]] with a hollow back. It most resembles a case binding in that it has a hollow back and visible joint, but unlike a case binding, it is built up on the book. Characteristic of the binding is the material covering the outside boards is separate from the material covering the spine. Many bookbinders consider the Bradel binding to be stronger than a case binding.<ref>{{cite book|last=Young|first=Laura|title=Bookbinding and Conservation by Hand: A Working Guide|year=1995|publisher=Oak Knoll Press|location=New Castle, DE|isbn=1-884718-11-6|pages=6–7}}</ref>

== History ==
The binding may be traced to 18th century [[Germany]]. The originator of the binding is uncertain, but the name comes from a French binder working in Germany, Alexis-Pierre Bradel (also known as ''Bradel l'ainé'' or ''Bradel-Derome'').<ref>{{cite book|last1=Roberts|first1=Matt|title=Bookbinding and the Conservation of Books|date=1982|publisher=Library of Congress|location=Washington, D.C.|isbn=0844403660|page=37}}</ref> The binding originally appeared as a temporary binding, but the results were durable, and the binding had great success in the nineteenth century.<ref>{{cite book|last=Cambras|first=Josep|title=The Complete Book of Bookbinding|year=2004|publisher=Lark Books|location=Asheville, NC|pages=52–53}}</ref> Today, it is most likely to be encountered in [[photo album]]s and [[scrapbooking|scrapbooks]].

The binding has the advantage of allowing the book to open fully, where traditional [[leather]] bindings are too rigid. It is sometimes modified to provide a rounded spine. This lends the appearance of a book where the paper is not suited to spine rounding; this is also to provide a rounded spine to a book too thin for a spine rounding to hold.{{Citation needed|date=February 2012}} The binding may also provide an impressive-looking leather spine to a book without incurring the full expense of binding a book in full or partial leather.

