{{Infobox musical artist |name=Cutumay Camones |image=Cutumay Camones Chicago 1987 069.jpg |origin=El Salvador |years_active=1982–1988 |past_members= Gabino, Ricardo, Israel, Lolo, Paco, Eduardo, Teresa |background=group_or_band }} '''Cutumay Camones''' was a band from [[El Salvador]], formed in 1982. Its stated objective was to recover Salvadorean cultural roots and to provide popular music for the [[Farabundo Martí National Liberation Front|national liberation movement]].
In May 1982, Cutumay Camones was formed by a directive from the [[Farabundo Martí National Liberation Front#Ejército Revolucionario del Pueblo (ERP)|People's Revolutionary Army of El Salvador]], a part of the [[FMLN]], as cultural ambassadors for the national liberation movement. The name comes from the [[Nahuatl]] for a town in [[Santa Ana Department|Santa Ana]] in western El Salvador, where the FMLN had an uprising in January 1981.
The group originally had three members: Eduardo, Gabino, and Ricardo, and two months later Paco, Teresa and Israel joined. By 1984, Lolo had joined, and eventually the group consisted of five permanent members: Lolo, Paco, Israel, Eduardo, and Teresa. Except for Eduardo, and Israel none of the members were musicians prior to joining. Cutumay Camones used different rhythms such as [[Mexican Son music|Son]] [[cumbia]] [[Classical guitar|classical]] and [[rancheras]], and instruments such as [[marimba]], [[accordion]], and [[Guitarrón mexicano|guitarrón]].
In 1988, the group officially disbanded.<ref name=Noticias>{{cite web|title=Cutumay Camones : Popular Insurgency And Music In El Salvador|author1=Almeida, Paul|author2=Urbizagastegui, Rubén|url=http://www.antropologia.com.ar/congresos/contenido/49CAI/Almeida.htm|publisher=Noticias de Antropología y Arqueología|accessdate=2 March 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140514061304/http://www.antropologia.com.ar/congresos/contenido/49CAI/Almeida.htm|archivedate=14 May 2014|df=}}</ref> Lolo left El Salvador in 1990 and later played in the band [[Los Jornaleros del Norte]]. He started a family and has a daughter named Alejandra.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jones|first=Bart|title=Musical group gives day laborers a voice|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20000806&slug=4035428|accessdate=19 March 2012|newspaper=The Seattle Times|date=6 August 2000}}</ref> Paco was assassinated in 1996 by the [[National Civil Police of El Salvador|National Civil Police]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Fifteenth Anniversary For Peace Accords: Moment For Reflection More Than Celebration|url=http://www.cispes.org/es/media/el-salvador-watch-newsletter/fifteenth-anniversary-for-peace-accords-moment-for-reflection-more-than-celebration/|accessdate=2 March 2012|newspaper=El Salvador Watch|publisher=Committee in Solidarity with the People of El Salvador|date=24 January 2007|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140514045935/http://www.cispes.org/es/media/el-salvador-watch-newsletter/fifteenth-anniversary-for-peace-accords-moment-for-reflection-more-than-celebration/|archivedate=14 May 2014|df=}}</ref> and Eduardo died in 2007 from cancer.<ref>{{cite news|last=Flores|first=Frankie|title=Muere Eduardo "El Holandés": La Voz de Cutumay Camones|url=http://www.diariocolatino.com/es/20070713/amigos/45018/Muere-Eduardo-%E2%80%9CEl-Holand%C3%A9s%E2%80%9D-La-Voz-de-Cutumay-Camones.htm?tpl=69|accessdate=2 March 2012|newspaper=Diario Co Latino|date=13 July 2007|language=Spanish|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140514020704/http://www.diariocolatino.com/es/20070713/amigos/45018/Muere-Eduardo-%E2%80%9CEl-Holand%C3%A9s%E2%80%9D-La-Voz-de-Cutumay-Camones.htm?tpl=69|archivedate=14 May 2014|df=}}</ref>
In 2012, Teresa from Cutumay Camones joined with members of another revolutionary Salvadron music group from the 1980s, Guinama, to form a new group. The fusion of these historic bands is called Cutumay Guinama. Their mission is to keep alive the memories of the sacrifices made for liberty during the civil war, and to continue promoting social change with their new recordings.<ref>Interview with Radio YSUCA on February 23, 2013</ref>
== Discography == * ''Vamos Ganando La Paz'' (1982) * ''Por Eso Luchamos'' (1984) * ''Patria Chiquita Mia'' (1987) * ''Llegó la Hora'' (1988)<ref name=Noticias/> * ''El Salvador, un Canto por la Memoria de Eduardo y Paco Contra la Explotacion Minera'' includes tree songs "Bolivar" recorded in Venezuela in the first "Festival de la cancion bolivariana" with the help of "Ali Primera" "Primer instrumental" a collection of traditional music in marimba and "Palomita Blanca" recorded in the former soviet union
